    <h1 id="heading1" class="text-center"><b>Urine Speciment</b></h1>

    <h3>Principles for urine specimen collection</h3>

    <p>
        Appropriate collection of urine specimens is critical to ensure the validity and
        reliability of results interpretation.
    </p>
    

    <p>
        Urine is normally a sterile body fluid, however, contamination by normal flora of
        the perineum, urethra and vagina can occur during collection
    </p>

    

    <p>
        Never submit urine collected in a bedpan or urinal.
    </p>

    

    <p>
        Urine can be collected at any time of day and can be stored for up to 24 hours in a
        refrigerator (2-5°C).
    </p>

    <p>
        Ensure the specimen is labeled, properly sealed and stored upright in the specimen plastic
        bags (in the compartment for sterile specimen jars).
    </p>

    <p>
        Early morning urine specimens have the best yield. However, do not miss the opportunity
        to collect the urine specimen at the time of consultation
    </p>

    



